Brisbane Challenge Cup

Premiership Final: Pineapple Rovers 3 Merthyr Thistles 1

1912-1918

Junior competition only. Competition was suspended in 1916 and 1917 due to World War One

 

 

Pineapple Rovers first appeared under this name as a junior club in 1912, and was distinct from earlier Rovers clubs in Brisbane.

The club celebrated its 25th anniversary in 1937: Soccer Reunion: Pineapple Rovers' Mark Anniversary (Brisbane Telegraph 30 Oct 1937, page 5).

Brisbane Division 2

 

 

United Rangers first formed as a junior club in 1932

 

Note on 1936 season: Round 5 (27/06/1936) United Rangers vs. Milton was abandoned with United leading 1-0, just after half time, when the Milton captain refused to leave the field when ordered off by the referee.

The BDFA ordered the game to be replayed, but only 'should the result bear upon the outcome of the premiership competition'. The game was not replayed.

However, United Rangers withdrew from all competition after 12/09/1936 (Telegraph 11/09/1936), and it seems the game was awarded to Milton after this date (and before 24/09/1936 when final standings were published in the Courier-Mail).

QFA - Division 2 (section B)

 

 

1922-1926

Inactive at senior level

 

 

 

A team playing as Merton Rovers first appeared in the junior fixtures for a single season in 1915.

The Merton Rovers Soccer Club whose record appears above was formed in 1922 and competed in junior competition from 1922 to 1926 before joining the senior ranks in 1927.

The club was suspended by the Queensland Soccer Council from competing in the 1938 season. It was referred to as defunct in contemporary media reports in 1939.

Merton Rovers reformed at the start of the 1940 season and then competed continuously at a senior level (except WWII) until it merged with Easts-Aston Villa prior to the 1970 season.

Norman United

Norman United competed in Brisbane Division 2 in the 1946 season early.

The club was taken over by Corinthians prior to the 1947 season and its players were transferred to Corinthians.
